  1: `Film Set Terminology & Professional Operations\par
*Academic Level: Industry Professional Certification*\par
\par
**Lesson 1.1: The 24-Hour Clock System \f1\endash  Professional Time Management**\par
\par
*Industry Standard Timekeeping*\par
The film industry operates on a 24-hour clock (military time) to eliminate AM/PM confusion during overnight shoots. Productions routinely run 14-16 hour days, and a 12-hour turnaround is the minimum legal requirement under ACTRA/UBCP collective agreements (Article 24: Hours of Work).\par
\par
> \f2\u9200?\f1  \f0 **Critical Knowledge**: "Call time" is when you must be *ready to work* in wardrobe and makeup, not when you arrive. Professional performers arrive 15-20 minutes before call time to account for parking, wardrobe checks, and sign-in procedures.\par
\par
**Professional Time Calculations:**\par
\f1\bullet  Time is tracked in 6-minute increments (0.1 hours) for payroll accuracy\par
\bullet  Example: 8 hours 12 minutes = 8.2 hours on your voucher\par
\bullet  **Overtime Calculation** (ACTRA/UBCP Standard Agreement Article 24.04):\par
  - Hours 1-8: Straight time\par
  - Hours 8-12: 1.5x (time and a half)\par
  - Hours 12+: 2x (double time)\par
\bullet  **Meal Penalty** (Article 24.07): If meal is delayed beyond 6 hours, production pays:\par
  - 1st hour delay: $13.50\par
  - 2nd hour delay: $18.00\par
  - 3rd+ hour delay: $22.50 per hour\par
\par
**Legal Protections Under ACTRA/UBCP:**\par
\bullet  Minimum 12-hour turnaround between wrap and next call (Article 24.06)\par
\bullet  Meal breaks required every 6 hours (Article 24.07)\par
\bullet  8-hour maximum before overtime begins\par
\bullet  Night premium: $30.00 for work between midnight and 6 AM (Article 24.08)\par
\bullet  Rest periods: 10 minutes rest for every 4 hours worked\par
\par
**Time Conversion Practice:**\par
Convert the following call times to standard time:\par
| 24-Hour | Standard | 24-Hour | Standard |\par
|---------|----------|---------|----------|\par
| 0545 | 5:45 AM | 1430 | 2:30 PM |\par
| 0730 | 7:30 AM | 1645 | 4:45 PM |\par
| 1245 | 12:45 PM | 2115 | 9:15 PM |\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 1.2: Professional Set Hierarchy \endash  The Assistant Director Department**\par
\par
*The Chain of Command \endash  ACTRA/UBCP Collective Agreement Definition*\par
\par
The Assistant Director (AD) department is your primary point of contact. Understanding their roles is essential for professional conduct.\par
\par
| Position | Responsibility | Interaction with Background |\par
|----------|----------------|------------------------------|\par
| **1st AD** | Sets the pace, manages the schedule, ensures safety, communicates with Director | Gives general direction to entire set; announces "rolling," "cut," "wrap"; manages the flow of the day |\par
| **2nd AD** | Creates call sheets, manages cast logistics, handles background logistics | *Your primary contact*; check in upon arrival; handles vouchers; communicates call times |\par
| **3rd AD** | Coordinates background action, crowd scenes, walk-ons | *Your direct supervisor*; gives specific direction for background movement; manages holding area |\par
| **2nd 2nd AD** | Large productions only, dedicated background handling | Manages large groups, organizes holding area, coordinates background movement |\par
\par
**Professional Protocol:**\par
\bullet  **Never approach the Director directly** \endash  all communication flows through the AD department\par
\bullet  **Listen for AD instructions** \endash  they may call your name or group\par
\bullet  **Ask questions to 3rd AD or Background Coordinator** \endash  they are your designated contacts\par
\bullet  **Violation of chain of command** is considered unprofessional and can result in being replaced\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8276?\f1  \f0 **Professional Insight**: The 1st AD is often called the "First." When you hear "First!" called across the set, stop what you're doing and listen for instructions. This is a production-wide command.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 1.3: Professional Background Cues and Commands \f1\endash  Essential Vocabulary**\par
\par
*Master These Commands \endash  They Are Used on Every Set*\par
\par
| Command | Meaning | Professional Response |\par
|---------|---------|----------------------|\par
| *"Picture's up"* | Cameras preparing to roll | Stop all movement, prepare for silence |\par
| *"Sound's up"* | Audio preparing to record | Complete silence |\par
| *"Roll sound"* | Start audio recording | Absolute silence |\par
| *"Roll camera"* | Start camera recording | Hold position, no movement |\par
| *"Rolling"* | Both sound and camera recording | *Freeze. Hold all movement.* |\par
| *"Speed"* | Camera and sound at proper speed | Continue only if directed |\par
| *"Background action"* | Start background movement | *Begin your business with energy, then settle into scene* |\par
| *"Action"* | Principal actors begin | **DO NOT move on "Action"** \endash  this is for principals only |\par
| *"Cut"* | Stop immediately | Freeze in place until "Reset" or "Back to one" |\par
| *"Back to one"* | Return to starting position | Move quickly but quietly to your first mark |\par
| *"Reset"* | Prepare for another take | Return to starting positions for next take |\par
| *"Going again"* | Another take immediately | Hold positions, don't reset |\par
| *"Lock it up"* | Absolute silence, everyone freeze | Stop all movement and noise immediately |\par
| *"Check the gate"* | Camera operator checks for debris | *Hold positions until you hear "Moving on" or "That's a wrap"* |\par
| *"Moving on"* / *"Next setup"* | Changing camera position | You may relax, but stay quiet |\par
| *"Strike"* | Taking down set | Stay clear of the area |\par
| *"That's a wrap"* | End of day or end of production | You are dismissed after signing out |\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 1.4: Professional Set Locations and Zones**\par
\par
*Know Where You Are \endash  Safety and Protocol*\par
\par
| Zone | Purpose | Rules | ACTRA/UBCP Reference |\par
|------|---------|-------|---------------------|\par
| *The Floor* | Active filming area | *Do not enter without being called* | General safety protocol |\par
| *Video Village* | Director/producer monitors | *Do not enter unless invited* | Production discretion |\par
| *Craft Services* | Food and beverages | Respect portions; crew eats first | Collective Agreement Article 31 |\par
| *Holding* | Background waiting area | Your designated area; stay here until called | Required facility under agreement |\par
| *Circus* | Main production area with trailers | Authorized personnel only | Production area |\par
| *Honeywagon* | Restroom trailers | Keep clean; report issues to AD | Required facility |\par
| *Hot Set* | Active filming area | **DO NOT ENTER. Never touch anything.** | Safety protocol |\par
| *Cold Set* | Not actively filming | Enter quietly only if directed | Safety protocol |\par
| *Strike Zone* | Equipment being removed | Stay clear | Safety protocol |\par
\par
> \f4\u9888?\u-497?\f1  \f0 **Safety Protocol**: A "Hot Set" means cameras are active or about to roll. Touching anything on a hot set \f1\endash  even moving a prop \endash  can ruin a take and cost the production thousands of dollars. **Do not touch anything on a hot set unless directed by an AD.**\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 1.5: The Voucher System \endash  Professional Payroll Documentation**\par
\par
*Your Voucher is a Legal Document*\par
\par
The voucher is your payroll record. ACTRA/UBCP collective agreements (Article 29: Vouchers) specify:\par
\par
\bullet  **Union Voucher**: For ACTRA/UBCP members; counts toward membership credits; higher rates; benefits contributions\par
\bullet  **Non-Union Voucher**: For non-members; does not count toward membership; lower rates; no benefits\par
\bullet  **Background performers do NOT sign vouchers** \endash  production signs them\par
\bullet  You sign to confirm attendance and verify your information\par
\par
**What to Verify on Every Voucher:**\par
1. Your name spelled correctly (must match ID for payroll)\par
2. Correct call time and wrap time\par
3. Overtime hours recorded (1.5x 8-12h, 2x 12+h)\par
4. Meal penalties if applicable ($13.50/$18.00/$22.50)\par
5. Night premium if applicable ($30.00)\par
6. Union status correctly marked\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-9020?\f1  \f0 **Professional Practice**: "If it's not on the voucher, it didn't happen." \f1\endash  Keep a photo of every voucher for your records. Errors can be corrected, but only if you have proof.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 1.6: Professional Etiquette Summary**\par
\par
*The Professional Performer's Code*\par
\par
| Rule | Rationale |\par
|------|-----------|\par
| Arrive 15-20 minutes before call time | Accounts for parking, wardrobe, sign-in |\par
| Sign in immediately upon arrival | Starts your pay clock |\par
| Stay in holding until called | Production needs to know where you are |\par
| Never sign out until dismissed by AD | Your pay ends when you sign out |\par
| Report any injury immediately | Required for workers' compensation |\par
| If you must leave holding, tell the Background Coordinator | You must be locatable |\par
| Speak quietly in holding | Sound carries to set |\par
| No phones on set floor | Distraction and safety hazard |\par
| No photography | NDAs and legal liability`,\par
\par
  2: `Background Acting Terms & Performance \endash  Professional Techniques\par
*Academic Level: Advanced Performance Studies*\par
\par
**Lesson 2.1: Professional Mark Technique \endash  The Foundation of Camera Awareness**\par
\par
*The Art of Hitting Your Mark*\par
\par
A "mark" is a piece of colored spike tape on the floor indicating your exact position for camera focus and lighting. Professional background performers hit their marks consistently without looking down.\par
\par
**Types of Marks:**\par
\bullet  **T-shaped tape**: Where your feet should be placed (toes at the crossbar)\par
\bullet  **Cross-shaped tape**: Precise stop points (center of cross is your position)\par
\bullet  **Colored tape**: Different colors for different performers or positions\par
\bullet  **Dry-erase marker**: Temporary marks on floors (fading, must be reapplied)\par
\bullet  **Apple boxes**: Wooden boxes used as standing marks for height\par
\par
**Professional Mark Technique \endash  The 5-Step Process:**\par
1. **Acknowledge your mark** \endash  know where it is before blocking; ask AD to show you\par
2. **Feel it with your feet** \endash  use peripheral vision, develop proprioceptive awareness\par
3. **Count steps** \endash  if walking, memorize your stride count (e.g., "3 steps to the mark")\par
4. **Use landmarks** \endash  corner of a table, edge of a rug, light fixture, door frame\par
5. **Land softly** \endash  stop without jarring or abrupt movement; practice smooth deceleration\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8273?\f1  \f0 **Professional Insight**: Actors who consistently miss their marks are often not rehired. The camera operator focuses on marks. Miss your mark = out of focus = unusable take = wasted production time and money.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 2.2: Continuity and Matching \f1\endash  The Invisible Art**\par
\par
*Why Continuity Matters \endash  From the Script Supervisor's Perspective*\par
\par
Continuity errors are among the most common mistakes in film. The Continuity Supervisor (Script Supervisor) documents every detail with photos and notes. Your job is to maintain consistency across all takes.\par
\par
**What Must Match Across Every Take:**\par
\bullet  **Physical positioning**: Same spot on floor, same hand placement, same body orientation\par
\bullet  **Prop handling**: Same hand, same grip, same timing (\f0\'b11 second)\par
\f1\bullet  **Walking path**: Same route, same speed, same stride count\par
\bullet  **Facial expression**: Same level of engagement/emotion; avoid "acting"\par
\bullet  **Clothing**: Same adjustments (jacket open/closed, sleeves rolled, collar position)\par
\bullet  **Hair**: Same position; don't tuck behind ear unless it was tucked in previous takes\par
\bullet  **Business timing**: If you pick up a cup at 5 seconds in take 1, pick it up at 5 seconds in take 2\par
\par
**Professional Continuity Protocol:**\par
\bullet  Take mental notes after each take \endash  what did you do, where were your hands?\par
\bullet  If something changes (your mark moved, prop changed), ask the AD to confirm continuity\par
\bullet  When in doubt, ask the Continuity Supervisor \endash  they have photos and will appreciate your professionalism\par
\bullet  Film yourself practicing to review your own continuity\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-8968?\f1  \f0 **Professional Insight**: The Continuity Supervisor takes Polaroid photos of every setup. They will correct you if you change something. Be grateful \f1\endash  they're saving your performance from continuity errors that could affect the final edit.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 2.3: Eyelines and Sightlines \endash  Professional Camera Awareness**\par
\par
*Eyeline \endash  Where You Look*\par
\par
Your eyeline determines where the audience believes you're looking. Incorrect eyeline ruins the illusion of the scene.\par
\par
**Professional Eyeline Directives:**\par
\bullet  *"Eyeline camera left"* \endash  Look to the left of camera (not at it)\par
\bullet  *"Eyeline camera right"* \endash  Look to the right of camera\par
\bullet  *"Eyeline mark"* \endash  Look at a specific taped X (often a person standing there)\par
\bullet  *"Eyeline off-camera"* \endash  Look at a person or object not in frame\par
\bullet  *"Eyeline to principal"* \endash  Look at the principal actor (for reaction shots)\par
\bullet  *"Eyeline to object"* \endash  Look at a specific prop or location\par
\par
> \f4\u-10179?\u-9151?\u-497?\f1  \f0 **Critical Rule**: **Never look directly at the camera unless specifically instructed.** This breaks the fourth wall and ruins the illusion. In professional terms, this is called "spiking the camera" and is considered a major error.\par
\par
*Sightline \f1\endash  The Camera's View*\par
\par
Your sightline is the path the camera needs to see you. Blocking another actor's sightline ruins their shot and wastes production time.\par
\par
**Sightline Rules:**\par
\bullet  Don't stand directly between camera and principal actor\par
\bullet  Don't walk through the frame during a principal's close-up\par
\bullet  Be aware of where camera is positioned at all times\par
\bullet  If you're unsure, ask the 3rd AD: "Am I in the shot?"\par
\par
*Cheating \endash  Professional Technique*\par
\par
"Cheating" is turning slightly toward camera while appearing to face another direction. This allows the camera to see your face while maintaining the illusion of natural orientation.\par
\par
**How to Cheat Properly:**\par
\bullet  Turn your body 15-30 degrees toward camera\par
\bullet  Keep your eyeline in the correct direction (use peripheral vision)\par
\bullet  Practice in a mirror to see what looks natural\par
\bullet  Ask the AD: "Is this cheating too much?" \endash  they'll adjust you\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 2.4: The "Furniture" Mindset \endash  Professional Philosophy**\par
\par
*Being Human Scenery*\par
\par
Your job is to create a believable world, not to be noticed. When the camera is on the principal actor, your movement should be subtle and natural.\par
\par
**Professional Principles:**\par
\bullet  **Be present, not performative** \endash  Your focus should be on your business, not on "acting"\par
\bullet  **If the Director is looking at you, you're doing too much** \endash  Background should blend into the environment\par
\bullet  **Create realistic business** \endash  Your activity should be what people actually do in that setting\par
\bullet  **Listen and react** \endash  Background performers react to principal actors, not to camera\par
\bullet  **Trust the director** \endash  If they haven't given you direction, your performance is appropriate\par
\par
> \f4\u-10178?\u-8559?\f1  \f0 **Professional Wisdom**: The term "furniture" isn't derogatory \f1\endash  it's a compliment. The best background performers create atmosphere so seamlessly that audiences never notice them individually. Your work is invisible but essential.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 2.5: Background Performance Techniques \endash  The Professional Toolkit**\par
\par
| Technique | Description | Professional Application |\par
|-----------|-------------|--------------------------|\par
| *Pantomime* | Silent acting without props | Essential for scenes where audio must be clean; practice in mirror; develop specific, repeatable gestures |\par
| *Business* | Your activity (reading, typing, serving) | Should be consistent and match scene's mood; have a beginning, middle, and end; can be practiced before shoot |\par
| *Cross* | Walking across frame | Timing must be precise; count steps; know entry/exit points; practice timing with AD |\par
| *Deep Background* | Far from camera, minimal detail | Good for beginners; focus on group movement; follow 3rd AD direction |\par
| *Featured Background* | Close to camera, detailed performance | Higher pay rate; may be given specific direction; more pressure; may have interaction with principal |\par
| *Atmosphere* | Group movement (crowd scenes) | Follow 3rd AD direction; stay with group; create group activity (talking, laughing, working) |\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 2.6: Equipment Safety \endash  Professional Protocol**\par
\par
*Never Touch Equipment \endash  It's Not Your Job*\par
\par
| Equipment | Department | Hazard | Professional Rule |\par
|-----------|------------|--------|-------------------|\par
| Camera | Camera Department | Expensive, delicate | Never touch cameras, lenses, tripods, dolly track |\par
| Lighting | Grip & Electric | Heat, electricity, heavy | Never touch lights, C-stands, flags, barn doors, stingers |\par
| Sound | Sound Department | Audio interference | Never touch booms, microphones, recorders |\par
| Props | Props Department | Breakable, valuable | Handle only when directed; hero props are irreplaceable |\par
\par
*If Equipment Blocks Your Path:*\par
1. Stop and wait\par
2. Call "Coming through" to alert crew\par
3. Ask AD or crew member to move it\par
4. Never step over cables \endash  ask for cable covers\par
\par
> \f4\u9888?\u-497?\f1  \f0 **Safety Protocol**: C-stands have counterweights. Moving one without knowing how can cause serious injury or damage. **Never touch equipment you haven't been trained to handle.**`,\par
\par
  3: `Set Etiquette & Professional Conduct \f1\endash  The Industry Standard\par
*Academic Level: Professional Certification*\par
\par
**Lesson 3.1: Professional Punctuality and Arrival Protocol**\par
\par
*Call Time \endash  The Non-Negotiable Standard*\par
\par
Your call time is when you must be *ready to work*, not when you arrive. Professional performers arrive 15-20 minutes early to account for:\par
\par
\bullet  Parking (may be off-site, requiring shuttle)\par
\bullet  Wardrobe changes (fittings, alterations, base wardrobe)\par
\bullet  Makeup checks (if required)\par
\bullet  Sign-in procedures (voucher verification)\par
\bullet  Holding area location (may be far from set)\par
\par
> \f2\u9200?\f1  \f0 **Professional Standard**: Being late is the #1 reason background performers are not rehired. Casting directors maintain databases with notes on performer reliability. A single late arrival can affect future opportunities with multiple casting offices.\par
\par
*If You Are Running Late \f1\endash  Professional Protocol:*\par
1. Call the 2nd AD or production office **immediately**\par
2. Have your voucher number ready\par
3. Give your estimated arrival time\par
4. Do not assume they will wait for you \endash  they often won't\par
5. Apologize and be prepared for consequences (may be sent home without pay)\par
6. Document the call (time, who you spoke to) in case of dispute\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 3.2: Professional Communication**\par
\par
*The Art of Being Seen but Not Heard*\par
\par
| Professional DO | Professional DON'T |\par
|-----------------|-------------------|\par
| Speak quietly in holding | Use phone on set floor (even on silent) |\par
| Ask questions to ADs or Background Coordinator | Approach Director or principal actors |\par
| Listen for AD instructions | Talk during takes |\par
| Signal if you need to leave holding | Wander onto set or into restricted areas |\par
| Use hand signals for communication during takes | Make unnecessary noise |\par
\par
*Professional Cell Phone Protocol:*\par
\bullet  Phones on **silent or off** at all times (vibrate can be heard on set)\par
\bullet  Never use phone on set floor \endash  step to designated "phone zones"\par
\bullet  No photography or video recording under any circumstances\par
\bullet  *Even "just for me" photos are prohibited and can get you blacklisted*\par
\bullet  NDAs are legally binding \endash  violations can result in lawsuits\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-8975?\f1  \f0 **Legal Notice**: Many productions require signing NDAs (Non-Disclosure Agreements). Violating an NDA can result in lawsuits with damages up to $50,000+. **Do not post anything about the production on social media.** This includes set photos, actor sightings, plot details, or even vague "working on a secret project" posts.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 3.3: Sign-In/Sign-Out Procedures \f1\endash  Protecting Your Pay**\par
\par
*Start of Day Protocol \endash  Your Pay Clock Begins*\par
\par
\bullet  Sign in **immediately upon arrival** \endash  this starts your pay clock\par
\bullet  Verify your name spelling matches your ID (payroll requires exact match)\par
\bullet  Check your voucher number against your call sheet\par
\bullet  Confirm "in" time is correct (to the minute)\par
\bullet  **Keep your voucher copy for tax records** \endash  you'll need it for CRA\par
\bullet  Take a photo of your voucher for your records\par
\par
*End of Day Protocol \endash  Your Pay Ends When You Sign Out*\par
\par
\bullet  Sign out when dismissed by AD \endash  **never before**\par
\bullet  Verify "out" time matches actual wrap (to the minute)\par
\bullet  Check for overtime hours (1.5x 8-12h, 2x 12+h)\par
\bullet  Verify meal penalties if applicable (delayed meal)\par
\bullet  Verify night premium if applicable (midnight-6 AM)\par
\bullet  Report errors **immediately** \endash  adjustments after wrap are difficult\par
\par
*Voucher Errors to Watch For \endash  Check Every Time:*\par
\bullet  Wrong name spelling\par
\bullet  Incorrect call time\par
\bullet  Incorrect wrap time\par
\bullet  Missing overtime hours\par
\bullet  Missing meal penalty\par
\bullet  Wrong union status (union/non-union)\par
\bullet  Missing night premium\par
\bullet  Wrong voucher number\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 3.4: Professional Conduct with Principal Actors**\par
\par
*The Golden Rules of Professional Distance*\par
\par
| DO \f2\u9989?\f1  \f0 | DON'T \f2\u10060?\f1  \f0 |\par
|-------|---------|\par
| Treat them as colleagues | Ask for autographs or photos |\par
| Make brief, professional eye contact | Stare at them |\par
| Respond if they speak to you | Approach them first |\par
| Be respectful of their space | Discuss their personal lives |\par
| Return to your business after brief interaction | Linger or hover |\par
\par
*If a Principal Actor Approaches You:*\par
1. Respond politely but briefly\par
2. Do not ask questions about the production\par
3. Do not share personal stories\par
4. Return to your business\par
5. Do not post about the interaction on social media\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8275?\f1  \f0 **Professional Wisdom**: Principal actors are working. Their focus is on their performance. Any distraction, even well-intentioned, can affect their concentration and the quality of the production. The set is their workplace, not a meet-and-greet.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 3.5: Craft Services Etiquette \f1\endash  The Professional Standard**\par
\par
*Respecting the Craft Services Area*\par
\par
Craft services is not a buffet \endash  it's a professional courtesy provided by production under collective agreement (Article 31: Meals and Craft Service).\par
\par
**Professional Rules:**\par
\bullet  **Take reasonable portions** \endash  one portion at a time; return for more later\par
\bullet  **Clean up after yourself** \endash  throw away trash, wipe spills, return dishes\par
\bullet  **Do not take food home** \endash  this is theft and can result in blacklisting\par
\bullet  **First team (principal actors) eat first** \endash  crew and background eat after\par
\bullet  **Don't rush the line** \endash  wait your turn; be patient\par
\bullet  **Respect labeled items** \endash  some items are for specific departments (e.g., "Camera Only")\par
\bullet  **Dietary restrictions** \endash  if you have allergies, inform craft services; don't assume accommodations\par
\par
*What Craft Services Typically Provides:*\par
\bullet  Water, coffee, tea, soft drinks\par
\bullet  Snacks (granola bars, fruit, nuts, chips)\par
\bullet  Hot meals on long days (breakfast, lunch, dinner)\par
\bullet  Dietary options (gluten-free, vegetarian, vegan, kosher, halal)\par
\bullet  Condiments, utensils, napkins\par
\par
*What to Bring Yourself:*\par
\bullet  Water bottle (refillable \endash  stay hydrated)\par
\bullet  Snacks if you have specific dietary restrictions\par
\bullet  Meals for very long days (if you prefer)\par
\bullet  Caffeine if you need it (some sets don't have coffee after lunch)\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 3.6: Wardrobe and Props \endash  Professional Handling**\par
\par
*Wardrobe Protocol \endash  Respect the Costume Department*\par
\par
\bullet  Arrive in "wearing" or "base" wardrobe if instructed (check call sheet)\par
\bullet  Wardrobe fitting is separate pay (usually 0.5 hour minimum)\par
\bullet  **Return all wardrobe at end of day** \endash  lost items may be charged to you (costume pieces can be hundreds of dollars)\par
\bullet  Report any damage immediately \endash  repairs are easier than replacements\par
\bullet  Do not alter wardrobe \endash  even pinning or hemming without permission\par
\bullet  Do not share wardrobe with others \endash  cross-contamination, sizing issues\par
\par
*Props Protocol \endash  Handle with Care*\par
\par
\bullet  **Do not take props home** \endash  this is theft and can result in blacklisting\par
\bullet  **Hero props** (featured items) are valuable and often one-of-a-kind \endash  handle with extreme care\par
\bullet  **Breakaway props** are designed to break \endash  handle carefully until instructed\par
\bullet  **Weapons** (even prop weapons) \endash  **never touch without direction from AD and armorer**\par
\bullet  Return props immediately when done \endash  don't leave them on set\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-9075?\f1  \f0 **Professional Note**: Hero props can be worth thousands of dollars and may be irreplaceable. Treat every prop as if it's the only one in existence.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 3.7: Bullying and Harassment \f1\endash  Know Your Rights**\par
\par
*ACTRA/UBCP Policy (Article 33: Harassment)*\par
\par
All performers have the right to a workplace free from harassment and discrimination. You are protected from retaliation for reporting in good faith.\par
\par
**What to Do:**\par
1. **Document everything** \endash  date, time, location, witnesses, exactly what was said/done\par
2. **Report to 2nd AD or Background Coordinator** \endash  they are required by collective agreement to investigate\par
3. **Contact your union** (ACTRA/UBCP) \endash  they have dedicated harassment hotlines\par
4. **Keep copies** of all communications (emails, texts, notes)\par
5. **Seek support** \endash  talk to trusted colleagues; don't suffer in silence\par
\par
*Production Responsibilities:*\par
\bullet  Must have anti-harassment policies posted\par
\bullet  Must have designated contacts for reports\par
\bullet  Must investigate complaints promptly\par
\bullet  Must protect you from retaliation\par
\bullet  Must provide a safe work environment\par
\par
> \f4\u9878?\u-497?\f1  \f0 **Legal Protection**: Under provincial human rights legislation and ACTRA/UBCP collective agreements, harassment and discrimination are prohibited. You cannot be fired or punished for reporting in good faith.`,\par
\par
  4: `Safety on Set \f1\endash  Professional Health and Safety Standards\par
*Academic Level: Occupational Health and Safety Certification*\par
\par
**Lesson 4.1: Your Legal Rights and Responsibilities**\par
\par
*Right to Refuse Unsafe Work \endash  ACTRA/UBCP Collective Agreement Article 25*\par
\par
> \f4\u-10179?\u-8479?\u-497?\f1  \f0 **Legal Protection**: "No performer shall be dismissed or disciplined for refusing to work in conditions they reasonably believe to be unsafe." \f1\endash  ACTRA/UBCP Standard Agreement Article 25.02\par
\par
*Your Legal Responsibilities Under Provincial OHS Acts:*\par
\bullet  You are required to refuse work that you believe may harm you or someone else\par
\bullet  Report any unsafe work to a Supervisor immediately\par
\bullet  If you observe unsafe conditions, report them \endash  do not assume someone else will\par
\bullet  Cooperate with safety investigations\par
\bullet  Know the location of first aid and emergency exits\par
\par
*Injury Reporting Protocol \endash  Immediate Action Required*\par
If you sustain an injury, no matter how minor:\par
1. Advise Background Coordinator immediately\par
2. Report to First Aid (location will be on call sheet)\par
3. Complete an Accident Report \endash  get a copy\par
4. Document everything: date, time, location, witnesses, what happened, equipment involved\par
5. See your family doctor as soon as possible (within 24 hours)\par
6. Follow up with production about medical coverage (WSIB/WorkSafeBC/WCB)\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-9013?\f1  \f0 **Professional Documentation**: Take photos of the area where the injury occurred (if safe). Write down names of witnesses. Keep a copy of the Accident Report. Your health comes first \f1\endash  never downplay injuries to avoid "causing trouble."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 4.2: Slips, Trips, and Falls \endash  The Most Common Injury**\par
\par
*Common Hazards on Set \endash  Prevention is Your Responsibility*\par
\par
| Hazard | Prevention | What to Report |\par
|--------|------------|----------------|\par
| Cables and cords | Use cable covers; tape down securely; ask for covers if missing | Exposed cables, loose tape |\par
| Wet floors (Honeywagons, rain, spills) | Report immediately; place warning signs; avoid wet areas | Standing water, no signs |\par
| Uneven terrain (location shoots) | Wear appropriate footwear; watch your step; ask for lighting | Hidden holes, loose ground |\par
| Stairs without handrails | Use three points of contact; ask for handrail | No handrail, poor lighting |\par
| Night shoots on roads | Stay in designated areas; wear reflective tape; ask for lighting | Poor visibility, moving vehicles |\par
| Props left in walkways | Report to AD; move to designated area | Obstructions, tripping hazards |\par
\par
*Professional Prevention Protocol:*\par
\bullet  Always be aware of your surroundings \endash  situational awareness is a skill\par
\bullet  Walk, don't run, unless directed for scene\par
\bullet  Use three points of contact on stairs (two feet, one hand)\par
\bullet  Wear appropriate footwear for terrain (no flip-flops on outdoor sets)\par
\bullet  Report hazards immediately \endash  don't wait for someone else\par
\par
> \f4\u9888?\u-497?\f1  \f0 **Safety First**: Most set injuries are preventable. If you see a hazard, report it. You may save someone from serious injury.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 4.3: Propane Heater Safety \f1\endash  Winter Shoot Protocol**\par
\par
*ACTRA/UBCP Safety Guidelines for Outdoor Winter Shoots*\par
\par
Propane heaters are common on outdoor winter shoots but pose serious risks if used improperly. Know these protocols.\par
\par
**Critical Safety Rules:**\par
\bullet  **Never close tent flaps completely** \endash  ventilation prevents carbon monoxide poisoning\par
\bullet  **Keep combustibles at least 1.37m (4 feet 6 inches)** away from heaters (ACTRA/UBCP standard)\par
\bullet  **Ensure propane tanks are level and secured** \endash  tipping can cause leaks\par
\bullet  **Never move or tamper with radiant heaters** \endash  only qualified crew handles them\par
\bullet  **Report any smell of gas immediately** \endash  this is a serious hazard\par
\par
*Carbon Monoxide Poisoning \endash  Know the Symptoms and Act Fast*\par
\par
| Symptom | Severity | Action |\par
|---------|----------|--------|\par
| Headache | Mild | Evacuate area immediately; get fresh air |\par
| Nausea | Moderate | Report to First Aid; do not re-enter |\par
| Dizziness | Moderate | Seek medical attention; do not drive |\par
| Confusion | Severe | Call 911; emergency medical attention |\par
| Breathlessness | Severe | Call 911; high oxygen treatment may be needed |\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-8536?\f1  \f0 **Emergency Protocol**: If you or anyone else has signs of CO poisoning, evacuate immediately and inform the supervisor. Do not re-enter the space until it has been declared safe by a qualified person (usually First Aid or location manager).\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 4.4: Environmental Illnesses \f1\endash  Weather Extremes**\par
\par
*Heat Stress Prevention \endash  ACTRA/UBCP Guidelines*\par
\par
| Stage | Symptoms | Action |\par
|-------|----------|--------|\par
| Heat Cramps | Muscle pain, spasms | Rest, hydrate (water + electrolytes), stretch |\par
| Heat Exhaustion | Heavy sweating, weakness, dizziness, nausea | Seek shade, hydrate, cool compresses, remove excess clothing |\par
| Heat Stroke | Confusion, loss of consciousness, high body temp, no sweating | **Call 911 immediately** \endash  this is life-threatening |\par
\par
*Cold Exposure / Hypothermia Prevention*\par
\par
| Stage | Symptoms | Action |\par
|-------|----------|--------|\par
| Mild | Shivering, numbness, blue fingers/toes | Seek warmth, remove wet clothing, warm gradually |\par
| Moderate | Confusion, slurred speech, drowsiness | Warm gradually, no direct heat (no hot water, no heating pad), seek medical attention |\par
| Severe | Loss of consciousness, weak pulse | **Call 911 immediately** \endash  life-threatening |\par
\par
*Production Responsibilities Under ACTRA/UBCP:*\par
\bullet  Provide adequate shelter in extreme weather (Article 25: Working Conditions)\par
\bullet  Allow warming/cooling breaks as needed\par
\bullet  Provide appropriate gear (waterproof for rain scenes, warm layers for cold)\par
\bullet  Have First Aid on site at all times\par
\bullet  Monitor weather conditions and adjust schedule as needed\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 4.5: Physical Hazards \endash  Professional Awareness**\par
\par
*Heavy Equipment Safety \endash  Know Your Surroundings*\par
\par
| Equipment | Hazard | Prevention |\par
|-----------|--------|------------|\par
| Cranes, jibs | Swing path, overhead objects | Stay behind safety line; listen for "swinging" call |\par
| Set structures | Falling objects | Hard hat if working near construction; stay clear of overhead work |\par
| Lighting | Heat, electrical, heavy | Never touch; report malfunction; stay clear of hot lights |\par
| C-stands | Counterweights, arms, tipping | Never move without crew; stay clear of arms |\par
\par
*Firearms and Pyrotechnics \endash  ACTRA/UBCP Protocol (Article 27: Weapons)*\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-8917?\f1  \f0 **Critical Rule**: **Never touch a prop gun, even if you think it's not real.** Only licensed professionals (armorers) handle firearms on set.\par
\par
\f1\bullet  Be aware of when and where firearms, explosives, pyrotechnics, open flames will be used (check call sheet)\par
\bullet  Make being safe your number one priority\par
\bullet  Stay behind the safety line\par
\bullet  Wear hearing protection when advised\par
\bullet  Follow all safety instructions from AD and armorer\par
\bullet  Do not joke about weapons \endash  safety is not a game\par
\par
*Laser Devices*\par
\bullet  Focus pullers may use laser measuring devices\par
\bullet  Ask if lasers are in use\par
\bullet  Avoid looking directly at lasers \endash  they can cause permanent eye damage\par
\bullet  Report any laser misuse\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 4.6: Vehicle Safety \endash  On-Set Driving**\par
\par
*Professional Vehicle Protocol*\par
\par
\bullet  Always wear seat belts when in vehicles on set (even parked)\par
\bullet  Follow direction of AD and Stunt Coordinator\par
\bullet  Drive slowly and predictably (5-10 km/h in staging areas)\par
\bullet  Be aware of crew members and equipment near vehicles\par
\bullet  Never drive under the influence \endash  this is immediate dismissal and blacklisting\par
\par
*If You're Asked to Drive:*\par
\bullet  If you're not a professional stunt driver, let someone else drive\par
\bullet  If you've never ridden a motorcycle or driven a boat, the set is not the place to learn\par
\bullet  Vehicle movement is part of the scene \endash  safety is priority\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 4.7: Working with Animals \endash  Professional Protocol**\par
\par
*Animal Actors \endash  Respect Their Training*\par
\par
\bullet  Animal actors are specially trained and handled by professionals (animal wranglers)\par
\bullet  Do not approach animals without the trainer's permission and supervision\par
\bullet  Even "friendly" animals can bite or kick when stressed or frightened\par
\bullet  If you're in a scene with an animal, talk to the trainer \endash  learn about the animal before "Action!"\par
\bullet  Report any animal-related concerns to the AD immediately\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 4.8: Intimate Scenes and Nudity \endash  Professional Protocols**\par
\par
*ACTRA/UBCP Intimacy Guidelines (Article 32: Intimacy)*\par
\par
An Intimacy Coordinator is required for any production involving nudity, semi-nudity, or simulated sexual activity.\par
\par
**Your Rights:**\par
\bullet  Know exactly what will be required before agreeing to work (Intimacy Rider)\par
\bullet  You cannot be forced to perform nudity or intimate scenes\par
\bullet  You can change your mind at any time \endash  this is your right\par
\bullet  Closed set protocols (only essential personnel present)\par
\bullet  Modesty garments provided\par
\bullet  Right to stop the scene if uncomfortable\par
\bullet  Chaperones available if requested\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 4.9: Stunt Safety \endash  Professional Protocol**\par
\par
*What Is a Stunt? (ACTRA/UBCP Definition)*\par
\par
A stunt is any performance that would be considered dangerous if not performed by someone with special training, or is beyond a performer's general experience or abilities.\par
\par
**Your Role:**\par
\bullet  A Stunt Coordinator decides whether a performance is a stunt \endash  they have final say\par
\bullet  If there is no Stunt Coordinator and you feel unsafe, let production know\par
\bullet  Suggest they get a qualified stunt performer \endash  this is your right\par
\bullet  Attend the on-set safety meeting if you're in a shot with a stunt\par
\bullet  Note: an increase in your fees will not make the performance any safer\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-9040?\f1  \f0 **Professional Wisdom**: Safety is paramount, not budget. No amount of money is worth injury.\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 4.10: Child Performer Protections**\par
\par
*Protecting Child Performers Act (Ontario) and Similar Provincial Legislation*\par
\par
\f1\bullet  Parental accompaniment required for young children\par
\bullet  Chaperones must have clean criminal record checks\par
\bullet  Right to refuse work \endash  children cannot be forced to perform\par
\bullet  Healthy food requirements \endash  production must provide appropriate meals\par
\bullet  Mandatory rest periods: 30-minute break every 3 hours for younger children\par
\bullet  Education time: school-age children require tutoring on set\par
\bullet  No nudity or sexual content for minors\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-9113?\f1  \f0 **Professional Responsibility**: Child performer protections are law. Do not bend rules to please production. The safety and well-being of young performers is paramount.`,\par
