| **Given Circumstances Journal** | Deepen character analysis | Write 2-page biography for every role |\par
| **Magic If Scenarios** | Activate imagination | Daily practice: "What would I do if..." |\par
| **Objective Trees** | Map character arc | Identify super objective \f5\u8594?\f1  \f0 scene objectives \f5\u8594?\f1  \f0 beats |\par
| **Emotional Memory Journal** | Build emotional vocabulary | Document sensory details of emotional experiences |\par
| **Script Analysis** | Apply all tools | Analyze one play per month |\par
\par
*Recommended Reading \f1\endash  Stanislavski System:*\par
\bullet  "An Actor Prepares" \endash  Constantin Stanislavski (foundational)\par
\bullet  "Building a Character" \endash  Constantin Stanislavski (physical expression)\par
\bullet  "Creating a Role" \endash  Constantin Stanislavski (character development)\par
\bullet  "The Stanislavski System" \endash  Sonia Moore (practical application)\par
\bullet  "The Actor's Art and Craft" \endash  William Esper (Meisner interpretation)`,\par
\par
  7: `Audition Technique (Shurtleff) \endash  The 12 Guideposts\par
*Academic Level: Professional Audition Preparation*\par
\par
**Lesson 7.1: The 12 Guideposts \endash  Overview**\par
\par
*From "Audition" by Michael Shurtleff \endash  The Complete System*\par
\par
Michael Shurtleff's 12 Guideposts are tools for analyzing scenes and auditions. They help you make specific, active choices rather than general, passive ones. Shurtleff cast over 500 Broadway shows and taught generations of actors.\par
\par
**The 12 Guideposts \endash  Quick Reference:**\par
1. Relationship \endash  Who are these people to each other?\par
2. Conflict \endash  What are they fighting for?\par
3. The Moment Before \endash  What just happened?\par
4. Humor \endash  What is funny in this scene?\par
5. Opposites \endash  What is the unexpected choice?\par
6. Discoveries \endash  What is new in each moment?\par
7. Communication and Competition \endash  Who is winning?\par
8. Importance \endash  Why does this matter?\par
9. Find the Events \endash  What changes?\par
10. Place \endash  Where are we?\par
11. Game Playing and Role Playing \endash  Who is pretending?\par
12. Mystery and Secret \endash  What is unsaid?\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.2: Guidepost 1 \endash  Relationship**\par
\par
*Who Are These People to Each Other?*\par
\par
Relationship is not general ("we're friends") but specific ("I need her approval because she's my boss's daughter and my promotion depends on her opinion").\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What is the history between these characters?\par
\bullet  How do they feel about each other? (Honestly, not what they say)\par
\bullet  What do they need from each other?\par
\bullet  What is the power dynamic? Who has more power? How does that affect behavior?\par
\bullet  How long have they known each other?\par
\bullet  What's unspoken between them? What are they not saying?\par
\bullet  How does their relationship change during the scene?\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8275?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "Relationship is the most important guidepost. If you don't know who these people are to each other, you can't play the scene."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.3: Guidepost 2 \f1\endash  Conflict**\par
\par
*What Are They Fighting For?*\par
\par
Conflict is the heart of drama. There is no drama without conflict. Conflict is not fighting \endash  it's opposing wants.\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What does each character want? (Be specific)\par
\bullet  How are those wants in opposition?\par
\bullet  Who is winning at each moment?\par
\bullet  What tactics are they using to get what they want?\par
\bullet  When does the balance shift?\par
\bullet  What's at stake? What happens if they lose?\par
\par
> \f4\u9876?\u-497?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "If you don't know what the conflict is, you don't know what the scene is about."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.4: Guidepost 3 \f1\endash  The Moment Before**\par
\par
*What Just Happened?*\par
\par
The Moment Before gives you immediate emotional preparation and entry into the scene. What were you doing? Where were you? How were you feeling?\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  Where was I just before the scene started?\par
\bullet  What was I doing?\par
\bullet  Who was I with?\par
\bullet  How was I feeling? (Specific emotion, not general)\par
\bullet  Why did I come here? What drove me to this moment?\par
\bullet  What am I bringing into this scene?\par
\par
> \f4\u9198?\u-497?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "The moment before is the launching pad for the scene. Without it, you have no takeoff."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.5: Guidepost 4 \f1\endash  Humor**\par
\par
*What Is Funny?*\par
\par
Find what is funny in every scene, even dramas. Humor comes from pain and unexpected situations. Don't play for laughs \endash  play the situation truthfully.\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What's absurd about this situation?\par
\bullet  Where is the irony?\par
\bullet  What unexpected thing happens?\par
\bullet  How do characters react to the ridiculous?\par
\bullet  What would make someone laugh if they were watching?\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-8700?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "Even tragedy has humor. Find it. It makes the tragedy more tragic and the comedy more real."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.6: Guidepost 5 \f1\endash  Opposites**\par
\par
*What Is the Unexpected Choice?*\par
\par
People are contradictory. Play the opposite of what is expected. If the line is "I love you," find the opposite ("I'm terrified of losing you").\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What is the expected choice? (Usually the first thing that comes to mind)\par
\bullet  What's the opposite choice?\par
\bullet  What contradiction is in the character?\par
\bullet  Where does the character hide their true feelings?\par
\bullet  What are they pretending? What mask are they wearing?\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-8956?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "Opposites create drama. The unexpected choice is almost always the right choice."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.7: Guidepost 6 \f1\endash  Discoveries**\par
\par
*What Is New?*\par
\par
Discoveries are what is new in the scene. What do you learn that changes things? Acting is reacting to discoveries. If there are no discoveries, the scene is dead.\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What does the character learn?\par
\bullet  What new information arrives?\par
\bullet  How does it change things? (Behavior, objective, relationship)\par
\bullet  What realization occurs?\par
\bullet  What surprise happens?\par
\bullet  How does the character's response change after the discovery?\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-9055?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "Every moment should be a discovery. If you're not discovering, you're not acting \f1\endash  you're reciting."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.8: Guidepost 7 \endash  Communication and Competition**\par
\par
*Who Is Winning?*\par
\par
Every scene is a competition. Someone is trying to get something, someone is resisting. Track who is winning moment to moment.\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What is each character trying to get? (Specific objective)\par
\bullet  What are they doing to get it? (Tactics)\par
\bullet  Who is succeeding? (At each moment)\par
\bullet  When does the power shift?\par
\bullet  What tactics are working? What tactics are failing?\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8250?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "In every scene, someone is winning and someone is losing. If you don't know who's winning, you don't know what's happening."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.9: Guidepost 8 \f1\endash  Importance**\par
\par
*Why Does This Matter?*\par
\par
Raise the stakes. Make it matter more. If it's not important to the character, it won't be important to the audience.\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What is at stake? (What will be lost or gained?)\par
\bullet  What happens if they fail?\par
\bullet  What happens if they succeed?\par
\bullet  Why does this matter now? (Urgency)\par
\bullet  What will they lose? (Love, money, dignity, life)\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-9016?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "Actors tend to play things too small. Raise the stakes. Make it a matter of life and death, even when it's not."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.10: Guidepost 9 \f1\endash  Find the Events**\par
\par
*What Changes?*\par
\par
Every scene has events that change the direction. Find them and play them. Events are the turning points of the scene.\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What happens in this scene? (List the events)\par
\bullet  What changes? (Objective, relationship, power, information)\par
\bullet  How does the character change?\par
\bullet  What is the turning point? (The moment where nothing is the same)\par
\bullet  What's the new direction after the event?\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-9011?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "Events are the architecture of the scene. Find them, play them, and let them change you."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.11: Guidepost 10 \f1\endash  Place**\par
\par
*Where Are We?*\par
\par
Be specific. A park bench isn't just wood \endash  it's where you got engaged. The coffee cup is stolen from your ex-lover.\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  Where exactly are we? (Specific location, not general)\par
\bullet  What does this place mean to the character?\par
\bullet  What history does this place have?\par
\bullet  How does the character feel about being here?\par
\bullet  What sensory details are here? (Sights, sounds, smells, textures)\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8224?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "Place creates mood. The more specific you are about where you are, the more specific your behavior becomes."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.12: Guidepost 11 \f1\endash  Game Playing and Role Playing**\par
\par
*Who Is Pretending?*\par
\par
People play roles: the victim, the hero, the innocent, the martyr, the seducer. Find what role your character is playing.\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What role is the character playing? (What mask are they wearing?)\par
\bullet  What are they hiding?\par
\bullet  What do they want others to think?\par
\bullet  What is the real self underneath?\par
\bullet  When does the mask slip?\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8275?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "We all play roles. The drama is when the mask slips and we see the real person underneath."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.13: Guidepost 12 \f1\endash  Mystery and Secret**\par
\par
*What Is Unsaid?*\par
\par
Every character has secrets. What isn't being said is often more important than what is.\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What is the character hiding?\par
\bullet  What don't they want others to know?\par
\bullet  What is the unspoken truth?\par
\bullet  What would happen if the secret came out?\par
\bullet  What is the character afraid of?\par
\par
> \f4\u-10178?\u-8917?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "The most important thing in any scene is usually what isn't being said."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 7.14: Audition Practical Application**\par
\par
*Putting It All Together \f1\endash  Your Audition Toolkit*\par
\par
**Before the Audition \endash  Preparation:**\par
1. Read the sides (script pages) 3-5 times\par
2. Apply all 12 guideposts to the scene\par
3. Make specific choices \endash  don't be general\par
4. Prepare to be flexible \endash  they may ask for adjustments\par
5. Dress appropriately (don't costume, but be in character's world)\par
6. Arrive early (15-20 minutes)\par
7. Warm up vocally and physically\par
\par
**During the Audition \endash  Performance:**\par
\bullet  Make eye contact with the reader or camera\par
\bullet  Use the space \endash  don't stand in one place\par
\bullet  Show range \endash  demonstrate opposites and conflict\par
\bullet  Take direction \endash  show you can collaborate\par
\bullet  Be prepared but flexible if asked to adjust\par
\bullet  Leave with your work, not your worries\par
\par
**After the Audition \endash  Follow Up:**\par
\bullet  Thank the casting director (briefly)\par
\bullet  Let it go \endash  don't obsess\par
\bullet  Learn from the experience \endash  what worked? what didn't?\par
\bullet  Continue to work on your craft\par
\bullet  Keep auditioning \endash  it's a numbers game\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8276?\f1  \f0 **Shurtleff**: "The audition is not about getting the job. It's about doing your work. If you do your work, the job will follow."`,\par
\par
  8: `Scene Study (Hagen) \f1\endash  The Actor's Craft\par
*Academic Level: Advanced Scene Study*\par
\par
**Lesson 8.1: Substitution \endash  Making It Personal**\par
\par
*From "Respect for Acting" by Uta Hagen \endash  Chapter 5*\par
\par
Substitution is replacing the character's circumstances with your own reality to make the situation personally meaningful.\par
\par
**How Substitution Works:**\par
\bullet  The character's circumstances become *your own*\par
\bullet  You use *your own experiences* to understand the character\par
\bullet  You transfer your *genuine feelings* to the character's situation\par
\bullet  The emotion is real, even if the cause is different\par
\par
**Example:**\par
> *The character's father just died. You substitute your own beloved dog who died. The grief is real, even if the cause is different. You don't pretend to grieve \endash  you grieve.*\par
\par
**Rules for Substitution \endash  The 5 Requirements:**\par
1. Must have *equivalent emotional weight* \endash  don't substitute minor for major\par
2. Must have *similar relationship dynamics* \endash  parent/child, friend/friend, lover/lover\par
3. Must be *specific and personal* \endash  not general ideas but actual memories and people\par
4. The substitution must be *appropriate* to the character's circumstances\par
5. You must be able to access the emotion *safely* \endash  don't harm yourself\par
\par
**How to Find Substitutions \endash  Building Your Emotional Archive:**\par
\bullet  Keep a journal of emotional experiences\par
\bullet  Note sensory details of important memories\par
\bullet  Identify what about a character's situation is similar to your own\par
\bullet  Find the emotional truth, not the literal event\par
\bullet  Work with a teacher to find appropriate substitutions\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 8.2: Endowment \endash  Giving Objects Meaning**\par
\par
*From "Respect for Acting" \endash  Chapter 7*\par
\par
Endowment is giving physical objects and places specific meaning and history. The coffee cup isn't just a prop \endash  it's the cup your character stole from their ex-lover's apartment.\par
\par
**How to Endow Objects \endash  The 5-Step Process:**\par
1. Choose an object or place\par
2. Give it a personal history (invent or use your own)\par
3. Connect it to a real object from your life if possible\par
4. Use all five senses to make it real (feel it, smell it, see it)\par
5. Treat the object with the appropriate significance\par
\par
**Examples of Endowment:**\par
\bullet  A photograph \f5\u8594?\f1  \f0 *the last picture of your mother before she died*\par
\f1\bullet  A letter \f5\u8594?\f1  \f0 *a love letter from a lost partner that you never sent*\par
\f1\bullet  A ring \f5\u8594?\f1  \f0 *a family heirloom passed down for generations*\par
\f1\bullet  A door \f5\u8594?\f1  \f0 *the entrance to a place you fear (or love)*\par
\f1\bullet  A window \f5\u8594?\f1  \f0 *a view of your childhood home you'll never see again*\par
\par
**The 5 Senses in Endowment \f1\endash  Make It Real:**\par
\bullet  What does it *look* like? (Color, texture, wear, light)\par
\bullet  What does it *feel* like? (Temperature, texture, weight)\par
\bullet  What does it *smell* like? (Perfume, dust, memory)\par
\bullet  What does it *sound* like? (Creak, rustle, silence)\par
\bullet  What does it *taste* like? (Memory, association)\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8319?\f1  \f0 **Hagen**: "The object is not the object. It is what it means to the character."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 8.3: The Fourth Side \f1\endash  Creating the Complete World**\par
\par
*From "Respect for Acting" \endash  Chapter 9*\par
\par
The "Fourth Side" is the imaginary wall that completes the room when acting in a three-walled set (the fourth wall is where the audience sits). Beyond the fourth side are the rest of the room, other characters who just left, and the world outside.\par
\par
**How to Use the Fourth Side \endash  Creating the World:**\par
\bullet  Imagine what is beyond the set \endash  be specific\par
\bullet  Create the rest of the room in your mind (furniture, walls, windows)\par
\bullet  Hear sounds from other rooms (traffic, voices, music)\par
\bullet  Feel the environment beyond the walls (temperature, weather)\par
\bullet  Allow your character to be affected by what's outside\par
\par
**Questions to Ask:**\par
\bullet  What is happening just out of sight? (Who else is there?)\par
\bullet  What do you hear from the next room?\par
\bullet  Who is waiting outside? (Or who just left?)\par
\bullet  What is the weather like?\par
\bullet  What is the world beyond this scene?\par
\par
> \f4\u-10180?\u-8229?\u-497?\f1  \f0 **Hagen**: "The fourth side is your link to the world of the play. Without it, you're acting in a vacuum."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 8.4: Object Exercises \f1\endash  Training the Senses**\par
\par
*From "Respect for Acting" \endash  Chapter 11*\par
\par
Object exercises train the actor's ability to create reality through physical action. They are the foundation of Hagen's technique.\par
\par
**Common Object Exercises \endash  Practice These:**\par
\bullet  Make breakfast *as your character* (full sensory reality)\par
\bullet  Pack a suitcase *to leave someone* (with meaning and urgency)\par
\bullet  Write a *difficult letter* (with emotional weight)\par
\bullet  Wait for *important news* (with anticipation and fear)\par
\bullet  Prepare for a *first date* (with nervousness and hope)\par
\bullet  Clean a space that *matters* to your character (with care and memory)\par
\par
**How to Do Object Exercises \endash  The Method:**\par
1. Don't indicate or pretend \endash  *actually do it* with full sensory reality\par
2. Use all five senses \endash  make it real\par
3. Focus on the task, *not yourself* \endash  let the character emerge\par
4. Allow the character to reveal themselves *through the action*\par
5. Repeat the exercise to refine it \endash  each time deeper\par
\par
**What Object Exercises Reveal \endash  Character Through Action:**\par
\bullet  How does your character handle objects? *Rushed or slow? Careful or sloppy?*\par
\bullet  What do they pay attention to? (Details? The big picture?)\par
\bullet  What do they ignore? (What doesn't matter to them?)\par
\bullet  What is their relationship to the physical world? (Master of it? Controlled by it?)\par
\bullet  What is their emotional state? (Anxious? Calm? Sad? Joyful?)\par
\par
> \f4\u-10178?\u-8744?\f1  \f0 **Hagen**: "Object exercises eliminate self-consciousness by focusing attention on the task rather than yourself. They ground you in reality and create truthful behavior."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 8.5: Professional Application \f1\endash  Scene Study**\par
\par
*Putting It All Together \endash  Your Scene Study Toolkit*\par
\par
| Exercise | Purpose | Frequency |\par
|----------|---------|----------|\par
| **Object Work** | Grounding in reality | Daily practice |\par
| **Substitution Practice** | Accessing genuine emotion | With every scene |\par
| **Endowment Work** | Making objects meaningful | With every prop |\par
| **Fourth Side Awareness** | Creating the world | In every rehearsal |\par
| **Script Analysis** | Understanding the scene | With every new piece |\par
\par
*Recommended Reading \endash  Uta Hagen:*\par
\bullet  "Respect for Acting" \endash  Uta Hagen (foundational)\par
\bullet  "A Challenge for the Actor" \endash  Uta Hagen (advanced)\par
