\par
  9: `Advanced Technique \endash  Masters of the Craft\par
*Academic Level: Professional Actor Training*\par
\par
**Lesson 9.1: Meisner Technique \endash  Living Truthfully Under Imaginary Circumstances**\par
\par
*From "Sanford Meisner on Acting" by Sanford Meisner & Dennis Longwell*\par
\par
The foundation of the Meisner Technique is "living truthfully under imaginary circumstances." It's about getting out of your head and responding to what's actually happening.\par
\par
**The Repetition Exercise \endash  The Core of Meisner:**\par
\par
*Setup:* Two actors sit facing each other. One makes an observation about the other ("You're wearing blue"). The other repeats with their own truth ("I'm wearing blue"). This continues, changing as behavior changes.\par
\par
*Rules of Repetition \endash  The 5 Commandments:*\par
1. *No planning* \endash  respond to what you see and hear in the moment\par
2. *No anticipating* \endash  don't think ahead; stay present\par
3. *No performing* \endash  just be yourself; don't "act"\par
4. *No judging* \endash  accept what happens; don't criticize\par
5. *Let it evolve* \endash  the repetition will naturally change as behavior changes\par
\par
**Purpose of Repetition \endash  What It Develops:**\par
\bullet  Get out of your head \endash  stop planning and thinking\par
\bullet  Stop anticipating \endash  respond to actual behavior\par
\bullet  Respond to what's happening \endash  not what you think will happen\par
\bullet  Develop listening skills \endash  truly hear your partner\par
\bullet  Build spontaneous reactions \endash  trust your impulses\par
\bullet  Connect with other actors \endash  real relationship\par
\par
**Independent Activity \endash  The Second Core Exercise:**\par
\par
Doing a physical task that has *meaning and urgency* (packing to leave someone, writing a difficult letter, preparing for a life-changing event). The activity must be important enough to be done even if you weren't acting.\par
\par
*Requirements for Independent Activity \endash  The 5 Conditions:*\par
1. Must be *difficult* enough to require concentration (not mindless)\par
2. Must have a *clear objective* (what you're trying to accomplish)\par
3. Must have a *deadline* (urgency \endash  must be done by a certain time)\par
4. Must be *important to you* (emotional investment)\par
5. Must have *obstacles* (something making it difficult)\par
\par
**Meisner: Emotional Preparation**\par
\par
Emotional preparation is the actor's process of generating necessary emotional state before entering the scene. It is personal and private \endash  using your own life, dreams, fantasies to create emotional reality.\par
\par
*How to Prepare \endash  The 5 Steps:*\par
1. Recall a personal experience that creates the needed emotion\par
2. Use sensory details to make it real (5 senses)\par
3. Allow the emotion to build organically \endash  don't force it\par
4. Do not rehearse the scene \endash  only the emotional state\par
5. Enter the scene with the emotion, not the memory\par
\par
*Rules for Emotional Preparation \endash  The 3 Protections:*\par
\bullet  Preparation must not be the scene itself \endash  you don't prepare the specific scene events, you prepare the emotional state\par
\bullet  Example: If the scene requires grief, you prepare by connecting to your own experiences of loss \endash  but not the specific funeral scene you're about to play\par
\bullet  Let go of the preparation when the scene starts \endash  use the emotion, not the memory\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 9.2: Stella Adler \endash  Script Analysis and Actions**\par
\par
*From "The Art of Acting" by Stella Adler*\par
\par
**Key Principles of Adler's Approach:**\par
\par
| Principle | Description |\par
|-----------|-------------|\par
| *Script Analysis* | Analyze the script for given circumstances \endash  don't miss anything. Research the time period, place, and culture. |\par
| *Actions, Not Emotions* | Focus on what the character does (actions), not just what they say. Physical actions reveal character. |\par
| *Imagination* | The actor must have a strong imagination and use it to create the world of the play. |\par
| *Size and Theatricality* | Actors must be larger than life while remaining truthful. The stage demands scale. |\par
| *Playwright's Intent* | Understand the playwright's intentions. The actor serves the writer. |\par
\par
**Stella Adler's Script Analysis Method \endash  The 5 Steps:**\par
1. Read the script many times (at least 5)\par
2. Research the time period, place, and culture (be specific)\par
3. Understand the playwright's intentions (what are they trying to say?)\par
4. Find the character's actions (not emotions \endash  what do they DO?)\par
5. Discover the character's journey (how do they change?)\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-8996?\f1  \f0 **Adler**: "The play is the actor's bible. Everything you need is in the text."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 9.3: Practical Handbook \f1\endash  Action Verbs and Beat Changes**\par
\par
*From "A Practical Handbook for the Actor" by Bruder, Cohn, Olnek, Pollack, Previto, and Zigler*\par
\par
**Action Verbs \endash  Play Actions, Not Emotions:**\par
\par
Action verbs are active, playable verbs that drive the scene. Instead of trying to play an emotion (sad, happy, angry), you play an action (to accuse, to console, to seduce).\par
\par
*Action Verb Categories \endash  Your Vocabulary:*\par
\par
| Category | Examples |\par
|----------|----------|\par
| *To affect* | move, touch, impress, stir, influence, sway, persuade |\par
| *To undermine* | weaken, sabotage, subvert, undercut, destabilize |\par
| *To charm* | attract, delight, enchant, captivate, woo, seduce |\par
| *To investigate* | examine, explore, probe, scrutinize, study, interrogate |\par
| *To provoke* | annoy, challenge, confront, goad, irritate, incite |\par
| *To beguile* | charm, enchant, entrance, captivate, bewitch |\par
| *To accuse* | blame, charge, condemn, indict, incriminate |\par
| *To console* | comfort, soothe, reassure, sympathize, calm |\par
| *To interrogate* | question, examine, cross-examine, grill, probe |\par
| *To protect* | guard, defend, shield, shelter, safeguard |\par
\par
*How to Use Action Verbs \endash  The 5 Steps:*\par
1. Choose a strong, active verb (not a state of being)\par
2. Make it specific to the moment (not general)\par
3. Play the verb, not the result (trust the process)\par
4. Be willing to change verbs as the scene changes\par
5. Let the action drive your behavior\par
\par
**Beat Changes \endash  The Architecture of the Scene:**\par
\par
A "beat" is a unit of action with a single objective. When the objective changes, the beat changes. Each beat requires a new action verb and objective.\par
\par
*How to Find Beat Changes \endash  The 6 Indicators:*\par
1. Shifts in topic \endash  when the subject changes\par
2. Changes in power dynamics \endash  when who's winning changes\par
3. Moments of discovery \endash  when new information arrives\par
4. When tactics fail \endash  when what you're doing isn't working\par
5. When energy shifts \endash  when the mood changes\par
6. When someone enters or leaves \endash  new dynamic\par
\par
> \f2\u9889?\f1  \f0 **Bruder**: "Playing actions rather than indicating emotions creates truthful, watchable behavior. The audience sees the pursuit, not the result."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 9.4: Actor's Thesaurus \f1\endash  Expanding Your Action Vocabulary**\par
\par
*From "Actions: The Actor's Thesaurus" by Marina Caldarone*\par
\par
**Action Verbs by Category \endash  Your Expanded Vocabulary:**\par
\par
| Category | Action Verbs |\par
|----------|--------------|\par
| *To affect* | move, touch, impress, stir, influence, sway, persuade, convince, inspire |\par
| *To undermine* | weaken, sabotage, subvert, undercut, destabilize, erode, dismantle |\par
| *To charm* | attract, delight, enchant, captivate, woo, seduce, beguile, entrance |\par
| *To investigate* | examine, explore, probe, scrutinize, study, interrogate, analyze |\par
| *To provoke* | annoy, challenge, confront, goad, irritate, incite, agitate, provoke |\par
| *To protect* | guard, defend, shield, shelter, safeguard, preserve, secure |\par
| *To attack* | accuse, blame, charge, condemn, indict, criticize, denounce |\par
| *To comfort* | console, soothe, reassure, sympathize, calm, pacify, comfort |\par
| *To pursue* | chase, follow, track, hunt, seek, pursue, pursue |\par
| *To escape* | flee, avoid, evade, dodge, elude, escape, retreat |\par
\par
**Using the Thesaurus \endash  Professional Application:**\par
1. Look up the emotion you want to create (not what you play)\par
2. Find the action that creates that emotion in others\par
3. Choose the *most specific* verb (not the most common)\par
4. Play that action truthfully (do it, don't think about it)\par
5. Let the emotion come as a result (trust the process)\par
\par
> \f3\u-10179?\u-8998?\f1  \f0 **Caldarone**: "Strong action vocabulary prevents generic acting. Specific verbs lead to specific behavior. The more precise your action, the more truthful your performance."\par
\par
---\par
\par
**Lesson 9.5: Professional Integration \f1\endash  Creating Your Technique**\par
\par
*Combining the Masters \endash  Your Personal Approach*\par
\par
| Master | Key Contribution | When to Use |\par
|--------|------------------|-------------|\par
| *Stanislavski* | Given circumstances, objectives, super objectives | Script analysis, character development |\par
| *Meisner* | Repetition, independent activity, emotional preparation | Rehearsal, scene work, being present |\par
| *Adler* | Script analysis, actions, imagination | Preparation, research, understanding |\par
| *Hagen* | Substitution, endowment, object exercises | Connecting personally to the material |\par
| *Shurtleff* | The 12 Guideposts | Auditions, scene analysis |\par
| *Practical Handbook* | Action verbs, beat changes | Moment-to-moment acting |\par
\par
*Building Your Personal Warm-Up \endash  Daily Practice:*\par
1. Physical warm-up (10 minutes) \endash  release tension, center yourself\par
2. Vocal warm-up (10 minutes) \endash  breath, resonance, articulation\par
3. Repetition exercise (10 minutes) \endash  with a partner, stay present\par
4. Independent activity (15 minutes) \endash  with meaning and urgency\par
5. Object exercise (15 minutes) \endash  with sensory reality\par
6. Script analysis (ongoing) \endash  apply to current material\par
\par
*Recommended Reading \endash  Complete Library:*\par
\bullet  "An Actor Prepares" \endash  Constantin Stanislavski\par
\bullet  "Building a Character" \endash  Constantin Stanislavski\par
\bullet  "Creating a Role" \endash  Constantin Stanislavski\par
\bullet  "Audition" \endash  Michael Shurtleff\par
\bullet  "Respect for Acting" \endash  Uta Hagen\par
\bullet  "A Challenge for the Actor" \endash  Uta Hagen\par
\bullet  "Sanford Meisner on Acting" \endash  Sanford Meisner\par
\bullet  "A Practical Handbook for the Actor" \endash  Bruder et al.\par
\bullet  "The Art of Acting" \endash  Stella Adler\par
\bullet  "Actions: The Actor's Thesaurus" \endash  Marina Caldarone\par
\bullet  "The Actor and the Target" \endash  Declan Donnellan\par
\bullet  "The Viewpoints Book" \endash  Anne Bogart\par
\par
> \f3\u-10180?\u-8417?\f1  \f0 **Professional Wisdom**: "Your technique is what you use when you're not inspired. When you are inspired, you don't need it. But without it, you won't be inspired when you need to be."`\par
\};\par
\par
export default function ModulePage() \{\par
  const \{ id \} = useParams();\par
  const router = useRouter();\par
  const [module, setModule] = useState<any>(null);\par
  const [progress, setProgress] = useState<any>(null);\par
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);\par
\par
  useEffect(() => \{\par
    loadModule();\par
  \}, [id]);\par
\par
  async function loadModule() \{\par
    const \{ data: moduleData \} = await supabase\par
      .from('modules')\par
      .select('*')\par
      .eq('id', id)\par
      .single();\par
    setModule(moduleData);\par
    \par
    const \{ data: \{ user \} \} = await supabase.auth.getUser();\par
    if (user) \{\par
      const \{ data: progressData \} = await supabase\par
        .from('user_progress')\par
        .select('completed, score')\par
        .eq('user_id', user.id)\par
        .eq('module_id', id)\par
        .maybeSingle();\par
      setProgress(progressData);\par
    \}\par
    setLoading(false);\par
  \}\par
\par
  const formatLessonContent = (content: string) => \{\par
    const lines = content.split('\\n');\par
    const elements: JSX.Element[] = [];\par
    let i = 0;\par
    let inList = false;\par
    let listItems: JSX.Element[] = [];\par
    let inTable = false;\par
    let tableHeaders: string[] = [];\par
    let tableRows: string[][] = [];\par
    \par
    while (i < lines.length) \{\par
      const line = lines[i];\par
      \par
      if (line === '') \{\par
        if (inList) \{\par
          elements.push(<ul key=\{`list-$\{i\}`\} className="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">\{listItems\}</ul>);\par
          listItems = [];\par
          inList = false;\par
        \}\par
        if (inTable) \{\par
          elements.push(renderTable(tableHeaders, tableRows));\par
          tableHeaders = [];\par
          tableRows = [];\par
          inTable = false;\par
        \}\par
        i++;\par
        continue;\par
      \}\par
      \par
      // Headers (###)\par
      if (line.startsWith('###')) \{\par
        if (inList) \{\par
          elements.push(<ul key=\{`list-$\{i\}`\} className="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">\{listItems\}</ul>);\par
          listItems = [];\par
          inList = false;\par
        \}\par
        elements.push(\par
          <h3 key=\{`h3-$\{i\}`\} className="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-700 mt-6 mb-3 border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-3">\par
            \{line.replace('###', '').trim()\}\par
          </h3>\par
        );\par
        i++;\par
        continue;\par
      \}\par
      \par
      // Bold headers (**)\par
      if (line.startsWith('**') && line.includes('** \f1\emdash ')) \{\par
        if (inList) \{\par
          elements.push(<ul key=\{`list-$\{i\}`\} className="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">\{listItems\}</ul>);\par
          listItems = [];\par
          inList = false;\par
        \}\par
        const [bold, rest] = line.split(' \emdash  ');\par
        elements.push(\par
          <h4 key=\{`h4-$\{i\}`\} className="text-md font-semibold text-purple-700 mt-4 mb-2">\par
            \{bold.replace(/\\*\\*/g, '')\} <span className="text-gray-600 italic">\emdash  \{rest\}</span>\par
          </h4>\par
        );\par
        i++;\par
        continue;\par
      \}\par
      \par
      // Tables\par
      if (line.startsWith('|') && lines[i+1]?.startsWith('|--')) \{\par
        if (inList) \{\par
          elements.push(<ul key=\{`list-$\{i\}`\} className="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">\{listItems\}</ul>);\par
          listItems = [];\par
          inList = false;\par
        \}\par
        inTable = true;\par
        tableHeaders = line.split('|').filter(h => h.trim()).map(h => h.trim());\par
        i += 2;\par
        while (i < lines.length && lines[i].startsWith('|')) \{\par
          tableRows.push(lines[i].split('|').filter(c => c.trim()).map(c => c.trim()));\par
          i++;\par
        \}\par
        continue;\par
      \}\par
      \par
      // Bullet points (\bullet )\par
      if (line.startsWith('\bullet ')) \{\par
        inList = true;\par
        listItems.push(<li key=\{`li-$\{i\}`\} className="text-gray-700">\{line.replace('\bullet ', '').trim()\}</li>);\par
        i++;\par
        continue;\par
      \}\par
      \par
      // Numbered lists (1., 2.)\par
      if (line.match(/^\\d+\\./)) \{\par
        inList = true;\par
        listItems.push(<li key=\{`li-$\{i\}`\} className="text-gray-700">\{line\}</li>);\par
        i++;\par
        continue;\par
      \}\par
      \par
      // Blockquotes (>)\par
      if (line.startsWith('>')) \{\par
        if (inList) \{\par
          elements.push(<ul key=\{`list-$\{i\}`\} className="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">\{listItems\}</ul>);\par
          listItems = [];\par
          inList = false;\par
        \}\par
        elements.push(\par
          <blockquote key=\{`quote-$\{i\}`\} className="border-l-4 border-blue-300 bg-blue-50 pl-4 py-2 my-3 italic text-gray-700">\par
            \{line.replace('>', '').trim()\}\par
          </blockquote>\par
        );\par
        i++;\par
        continue;\par
      \}\par
      \par
      // Regular text\par
      if (inList) \{\par
        elements.push(<ul key=\{`list-$\{i\}`\} className="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">\{listItems\}</ul>);\par
        listItems = [];\par
        inList = false;\par
      \}\par
      \par
      // Process inline formatting\par
      let processedLine = line;\par
      processedLine = processedLine.replace(/\\*\\*(.*?)\\*\\*/g, '<strong class="text-blue-800">$1</strong>');\par
      processedLine = processedLine.replace(/\\*(.*?)\\*/g, '<em class="text-gray-600 italic">$1</em>');\par
      \par
      elements.push(\par
        <p key=\{`p-$\{i\}`\} className="text-gray-700 mb-3" dangerouslySetInnerHTML=\{\{ __html: processedLine \}\} />\par
      );\par
      i++;\par
    \}\par
    \par
    if (inList) \{\par
      elements.push(<ul key=\{`list-final`\} className="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">\{listItems\}</ul>);\par
    \}\par
    if (inTable) \{\par
      elements.push(renderTable(tableHeaders, tableRows));\par
    \}\par
    \par
    return elements;\par
  \};\par
  \par
  const renderTable = (headers: string[], rows: string[][]) => \{\par
    return (\par
      <div key=\{`table-$\{Date.now()\}`\} className="overflow-x-auto my-4">\par
        <table className="min-w-full border-collapse border border-gray-200">\par
          <thead className="bg-gray-100">\par
            <tr>\par
              \{headers.map((h, idx) => (\par
                <th key=\{idx\} className="border border-gray-200 px-4 py-2 text-left font-semibold">\{h\}</th>\par
              ))\}\par
            </tr>\par
          </thead>\par
          <tbody>\par
            \{rows.map((row, ridx) => (\par
              <tr key=\{ridx\} className="hover:bg-gray-50">\par
                \{row.map((cell, cidx) => (\par
                  <td key=\{cidx\} className="border border-gray-200 px-4 py-2">\{cell\}</td>\par
                ))\}\par
              </tr>\par
            ))\}\par
          </tbody>\par
        </table>\par
      </div>\par
    );\par
  \};\par
\par
  if (loading) return <div className="p-4 text-center">Loading...</div>;\par
  if (!module) return <div className="p-4 text-center">Module not found</div>;\par
\par
  const isCompleted = progress?.completed;\par
  const content = LESSONS[module.module_number] || `## $\{module.title\}\\n\\nComplete this module and pass the test with 12/15 to unlock the next module.`;\par
\par
  return (\par
    <div className="max-w-3xl mx-auto p-4">\par
      <div className="bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-600 to-purple-600 text-white p-6 rounded-2xl mb-6">\par
        <h1 className="text-3xl font-bold">\{module.title\}</h1>\par
        <p className="text-blue-100 mt-2">Module \{module.module_number\} of \{module.section === 1 ? '5' : '4'\}</p>\par
      </div>\par
      \par
      \{isCompleted && (\par
        <div className="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 p-4 rounded mb-6">\par
          <p className="text-green-700 font-medium">\f2\u10003?\f1  \f0 Module Completed!</p>\par
          <p className="text-green-600 text-sm">Score: \{progress?.score\}/15</p>\par
        </div>\par
      )\}\par
      \par
      <div className="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-lg p-6 mb-6 prose prose-blue max-w-none">\par
        \{formatLessonContent(content)\}\par
      </div>\par
      \par
      <button\par
        onClick=\{() => router.push(`/module/$\{id\}/quiz`)\}\par
        className="w-full bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-600 to-purple-600 text-white py-3 rounded-xl font-medium hover:opacity-90 transition"\par
      >\par
        \{isCompleted ? '\f3\u-10179?\u-8995?\f1  \f0 Retake Test' : '\f3\u-10179?\u-8995?\f1  \f0 Take Module Test'\} (12/15 to pass)\par
      </button>\par
    </div>\par
  );\par
\}\lang9\par
}
